**Bolded call out box >: Your application does currently not meet enrollment requirements for Medicaid. Take action in the next 30 days.** 

**<Body>:** Our records indicate that you do not currently meet the 80-hour work-related requirements to be eligible for Medicaid. You have 30 days to demonstrate that you meet the requirements before your application is denied. In the future, you must demonstrate that you meet the new eligibility requirements every 6 months to renew your coverage.  
Because you are not eligible for enrollment in coverage through DC Health Link, you also cannot get tax credits or cost-sharing reductions. 


**<Header> What are my options?** 
**1. Meet the new work-related requirements** 
You must provide documentation of your work-related activities in order to meet the new requirements. You are required to demonstrate you have spent 80 hours per month doing any combination of the following activities:  
  **Work:** Working at a job or self-employment. 
  **Education:** Attending an educational program at least half time.  
  **Job training:** Participating in an employment and Training program to learn job skills and help you find a job. 
  **Community service:** Participating in community service (unpaid work for nonprofits, faith-based organizations, government agencies, etc). 

   You can submit activities in any of the following ways:  
      * Online: *Add info here* 
      * ___ App: *Add info here* 
      * In-person: *Add info here* 
      * Mail: *Add info here*  

**2. Check if you qualify for a short-term hardship exemption** 
If you cannot participate in work-related activities, you may qualify for a short-term hardship exemption. Short-term hardships describe circumstances beyond your control. You can be temporarily excused from work requirements because of:  
  * Personal illness  
  * Death or illness of a household member requiring the presence of the TFLA recipient in the home  
  * Unavailability of transportation 
  * Lack of work (employer must verify)  
  * Household emergency 
  * Temporarily unfit for work. 

**3. Check if you qualify for an exemption** 
You may be excused from the 80-hour monthly work-related requirement if you qualify for an exemption. If an exemption applies to you, you can keep Medicaid coverage without having to work, participate in job training activities, or complete community service.  
You can be exempt if you are:  
  * Medicare enrolled: *Elaborate* 
  * Incarcerated/recently incarcerated: *Elaborate* 
  * Former foster care youth: *Elaborate* 
  * Native American or Alaskan Native: *Elaborate* 
  * A parent or caregiver: *Elaborate* 
  * Pregnant or post-partum: *Elaborate* 
  * A veteran: *Elaborate* 
  * Medically frail: *Elaborate* 
  * In treatment: *Elaborate* 
  * Already meeting other requirements: *Elaborate* 

 If any of the exemption situations above apply to you, contact your local office immediately. 

**What kinds of documents are acceptable to meet work-related activity requirements?**  

**For employment:**  
  * A paystub showing your income for at least one full month  
  * An official notice from your employer that says how much you were paid and how many hours you worked  
  Note: Seasonal workers must earn an average of at least $580 per month for the past six months.  

**For education:**  
  * A transcript, a printout of your class schedule, or a report card  
  * An official letter from your school that says you were/are enrolled and how many credits or hours you received  
  * Financial aid or loan documents  

**For job training:** 
  * Enrollment documents  
  * An official letter from the program that says you are participating and how many hours you spend per month in training  

**For community volunteering:** 
* A document that lists the organization(s) you volunteer for and how many hours you volunteered each month  
* A letter from each organization you volunteered with that says how many hours you volunteered each month  

If you don’t meet the 80 hours per month with one activity, provide everything you are able to so that we can determine your eligibility. If we need additional information, we will reach out. 

 
**What happens when I submit my documentation?**

You may be determined eligible:  
If the additional information or documentation you submit meets the eligibility requirements, you will receive a notice saying you are eligible for Medicaid. You will be enrolled. 

You may be determined ineligible:  
If the 30 days pass without sufficient documentation and you are deemed ineligible, you will receive a termination notice. If you are disenrolled, you can: 
* Reapply for coverage online 
* Visit the ___ site and create or sign into your account to submit an application. 
* Reapply for coverage in person 
* Visit your local office or assistance center. 

 
